search the internet for common mistakes for butter emulsion and keep it short
<function_call name="search_perplexity"> <argument name="query">common mistakes for butter emulsion</argument> </function_call>

Common mistakes in **butter emulsion** (like beurre blanc or hollandaise) include overheating, poor temperature control, and improper incorporation, leading to separation.

- **Overheating or wrong temperature**: Butter melts too fast or burns, breaking the emulsion; "pay careful attention to the smoke point" and avoid high heat to prevent "burning the butter"[1](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ri3Koxefm0w).
- **Over-softening/melting butter**: Use softened (not melted) butter; if "you let it sit out for too long... the mixture could turn your baked goods gummy," which applies to emulsions too[1](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ri3Koxefm0w).
- **Insufficient creaming/mixing**: Not mixing long enough fails emulsion; "if you don't cream it long enough you won't get Peaks"[1](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ri3Koxefm0w).
- **Violating emulsification rules**: Follow simple rules for stages; "The Really Simple Rule of Emulsification" stresses proper fat-water balance to avoid separation[2](https://www.youtube.com/shorts/gitCR-iTofw).
